    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-05-14T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-05-14T05:00:00-05:00" n="44"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d44">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/1758</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PTN1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-05-14T11:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 14, 1915, 11 a. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 1 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>273. <persName corresp="#p_SA1">Salandra</persName>’s ministry resigned suddenly
                    last evening. Last Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_GG1">Giolitti</persName>
                    who has majority in Chamber holds that Austria concedes or will concede
                    sufficient to obviate necessity of war with attendant sacrifices. It is rumored
                    that <persName corresp="#p_SBS1">Sonnino</persName>, Minister for Foreign
                    Affairs, whom <persName corresp="#p_GG1">Giolitti</persName> strongly opposed,
                    was more in favor of war than <persName corresp="#p_SA1">Salandra</persName>.
                        <persName corresp="#p_GG1">Giolitti</persName>’s antiwar policy seems to
                    dominate for the present. Some excitement exists and morning paper even
                    [suggests] possibility of revolution.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PTN1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nelson Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
